column14:
Production:
45 minutes x 5 people = 225 minutes per release
225 minutes x 24 biweekly releases = 5400 minutes annually
Lower env testing/ CFQA:
45 minutes x 2 people (1 dev/ 1 pm min.) = 90 minutes per release
90 minutes x 24 biweekly releases = 2160 minutes annually
With 5 People (4 Devs/1 PM) Testing in Production:
Sum of 5400 + 2160 = 7560 minutes per year
7560 = 126 hours saved annually
[126 hours ÷ 40 hour/week = 3.15 work weeks]
With 7 People (6 Devs/1 PM) Testing in Production:
Sum of 7560 + 2160 = 9720 minutes per year
9720 = 162 hours saved annually
[162 hours ÷ 40 hour/week = 4.05 work weeks]

column4: The Automated Navigator-Fusion application streamlines the process of sending reports to MailToBorrower and Signing Approvals. column3: FirstFunding Wire Audit Review screens Performance improvement
column4: The Wire Audit Review screens have been problematic since FirstFunding's increased volume levels.  The working screen for that part of the application had reached an average load time of 20+ seconds, and every loan FirstFunding funds has to go through that process.  After some discovery, Steve was able to find some expensive queries embedded in the process, some of which were no longer needed in the application.  After some clean up and some optimization, that same page now hits an average load time of 300ms.  FirstFunding is now funding around 10,000 loans per month.  So that is a 20 second improvement for 10k loans every month. That's an estimated savings to the operation team of 3,333 minutes (56 hours) per month!  Definitely something we will add to our toil-busting numbers!
column5: All users on the FirstFunding Production system: FirstFunding Operations Team
column6: Improved application responsiveness system wide. This page is loaded multiple times for every loan, and hits the database every time. As a result every time the page is loaded, there is an effect on any user navigating or using the system to edit or load data.
column10:
20 seconds per loan load
1200000 loans per year
20 * 120000 = 2,400,000 seconds
/60 = 40,000 minutes
/60 = 667 hours
column11: Code is in production. We're saving already and our Production OTEL confirms the performance has improved.
